						<div class="postbody">Actually the &quot;64 shift&quot; though made me think a little more minimally: if a nonzero value in the oversize ROM nybble just specified that the original byte 4/5 is now an exponent, the range now easily extends from 1 byte to eternity. Could even use the 15 values to specify an odd multiplier to accomodate 14 different varieties of non-power-of-two sizes.<br /><br />0 -&gt; (original 16k * N)<br />1-15 -&gt; 2^N * [1,3,5,7,9,11,13,15,17...]<br /><br />Kind of turns the original byte into a &quot;chip address size&quot; and the oversize nybble into a &quot;chip count&quot;.<br /><br /><br />(I'm just golfing here, though. I'm not personally very interested in gigantic ROMs. The existing size spec is plenty good enough for everything I selfishly care about.)</div>

